reviews.text: BE AWARE!  Please review your bill. It is impossible to decipher because it is in Chinese...  In my case they charged for an extra item I did not order. They corrected it.  Then they charged suggested gratuity as the full bill amount adding an extra tip line in your voucher. If you do not pay attention (like I did) you will end up paying 30% tip for an average service. I will dispute this charge with my cc company. I hope it was an honest mistake by the restaurant. To be honest the food was good. We ordered a salt and pepper crab and it was good. The service is good but not spectacular. In our case the staff was courteous.

Good food, service speed so and so, staff manager is helpful and accommodating, not all staff members speak English fluently but we didn't have any problems. Chinese people seem to dine there as well! They add 10% tip on their own but when we gave a credit card for payment we asked that only the food amount is charged and that we will choose the tip amount, and so it was done.

The young Asian male server did an extremely rude thing that I've never experienced or heard of in my life. He shamelessly asked me why I did not tip., as though I had to tip. First, the whole meaning of the word ‚Äòtip‚Äô is something that is discretionary by nature. Everyone knows that, and it always has been that way. Also, the reason that I did not tip was that the bill, including the restaurants‚Äô reasonable profit, was an unfair price. The food was slightly above average in quality, but was smaller than average in quantity. And that means that it was average overall. The fair price, in San Francisco‚Äôs Chinatown, for the particular meal that I ordered is no more than $13. Yet, the bill was $18. So, to me, I effectively already paid the tip by paying for the bill. And I can not afford to give free money away. I did not give that server the reason, however, because I'm not required to do so. Even still, he would not leave the table and kept being more and more demanding about ‚Äòno tip‚Äô being given. After I left the restaurant, he followed me outside and told me that I ‚Äòshould give a reason for not giving a tip‚Äô. I told him that he now was harassing me and that if he didn't stop, that I would call the police on him for it. And I pointed out that, no, I should not give a reason for not giving a tip. I don't have to do so. And virtually no customer, in America and including in any Chinatown, ever has done so. Similar treatment was given to me by a server at a restaurant across the street, in response to a ‚Äòlow tip‚Äô. And articles have been published about San Francisco servers demanding ‚Äòmandatory tips‚Äô. Yet, there's no such thing as a ‚Äòmandatory tip‚Äô. Because if they were mandatory, then they wouldn't be tips. San Francisco servers need to stop being so rude to their customers. And if they're not getting paid enough, then they need to protest their greedy restaurant owners.

DO NOT GO HERE. ONLY EAT HERE IF YOU WANT HORRIBLE SERVICE AND FOOD POISONING!!! My wife and I were looking for a nice Chinese restaurant to cap off our great day in San Francisco so we thought this place would be great... WE COULD NOT HAVE BEEN MORE WRONG. We get in there and chose our food... then the waiting began. The guy right next to me who came in after we ordered got the same exact food and was served before me or my wife got our food. Then TWO OTHER tables got the same thing. 25 minutes later we finally got our food which was lower than sub-par. The beef my wife got was cold while the chicken I got was soggy and nowhere near my expectations. On top of the negligent service and bad food they had the audacity to add an 18% tip. When we asked about they said it was "Suggested tip". The worst part is that my wife now has FOOD POISONING from the terrible, cold beef that we got.

Food was good.

Ferry Building.name: Ferry Building

reviews.text:
Indulge in the unique San Francisco history experience layered with a variety of  artisan stores and eateries offering a wide range of sensory adventures.  

Enjoy the spacious landmark building that San Franciscans used since 1898 as their point of departure to the East Bay and Marin cities.  Stop at one of the many stores purveying food, plants, and household goods.  Shop for the unusual fungi, tasty pig parts  and mouth watering desserts. Join the crowds sipping delicious Blue Bottle coffee at the open bar.   Savor the modern Vietnamese cuisine at the legendary Slanted Door restaurant or grab one of their noodle soups at the takeout location.  

Wrap up the experience by shopping for fresh local produce at the outdoor Farmers Market open on Saturdays and selected weekdays.

When you visit California, you have to spend an hour or two at the Ferry Building. There's so much going on there. You'll taste the highest quality food on earth. You'll look out onto the Bay and watch the Ferries come and go. My favorite time is in the early mornings and late afternoons when the commuters from across the bay use the ferries.

I haven't actually tried any of the places inside, but it's such a cool spot. Nicely decorated and aesthetically cared for. All businesses seem local and personally/family managed, no chains. Some artsy craftsy stores. Really cool atmosphere!

Best time to visit is during the Saturday Farmers Market on a sunny day... (which can be sporadic). This is a major SF place you need to check out. All sorts of organic and healthy living stuff going on in addition to lots of yummy food stalls. There's some interesting places inside the ferry building to check out and I always enjoy getting ice cream or a cup of coffee from blue bottle to chill by the dock.

Amazing food - raw produce, baked goods, and full masks from the Mexican stand. Free samples of rich juicy fruit and baked goods. The best smoked fish anywhere at Captain Mike's - sandwiches, to go, jerky, and of course free samples - from a storybook character. And bench seating to chow down this beautiful food with a spectacular view of the Bay Bridge. Life just doesn't get better!

reviews.text:
Beautiful winding street, synonymous with the character of San Francisco. 

You can't come to SF without seeing iconic Lombard street, but please be respectful. The huge crowds of tourists have negatively impacted the locals who live on Lombard so they will soon close it to car traffic. Let's make sure that it will not be closed to pedestrian access by staying on the walk, off the residents stoops and stairways and cleaning up after yourself.

Two friends were visiting from across the country so I took them about the city. Lombard Street is a unique and fascinating landscape. Only thing I would suggest is to be respectful of traffic around you. People do live here as well! Great attraction from top to bottom.

A drive down Lombard Street is not for the weak hearted. It is a fun place. Walking around this place is great. The place is always crowded. You will never be disappointed visiting this place anytime around the year. But, finding parking around this place is almost impossible. Park near the Piers and walk/take a bus ride to Lombard Street to avoid traffic backup when getting out of this place.

Pretty neat to check out if you've never been before. There's not much here other than the street though, it's busy with tourists taking pictures walking up and down and tourists driving down the street. Overall nice but nothing super about it.

You can't go to San Francisco without going to Lombard Street but no matter what time of day you go and no matter how early/late you think you'll get there, it will always be packed and you'll never get the perfect photo, so bear that in mind. It's a beautiful street best enjoyed on a sunny day so the flowers pop in your photos but definitely see it from both the top and bottom of the hill. While you're there, catch a glimpse of Alcatraz and throw in the cable car for good measure.

We loved our stay here! The owner is very kind and you can tell that he really cares about his business succeeding. The location is good and the price is very fair. The rooms were clean and we felt secure. I highly recommend staying here! You will not be disappointed.

Bed bugs.  Room seemed surprisingly nice at first, but woke up with a series of bites.

Manager ignored me for 10 minutes while he was making what appeared to be a personal telephone call.  He was similarly slow when we spoke on the phone.

He quoted me a price on the phone ($129) which it turned out did not include tax or other 'miscellaneous charges'.  Total was $162.79.  This was despite his stating that I was getting a discount for taking a non-smoking room (I don't smoke) - shady.

I was also asked to move my car from the street (all spaces owned by the hotel were full) and squeeze it into an unmarked spot.

The owner was very friendly and extremely accommodating. He allowed us to park in the lot before check in time so that we could walk to the Giants game. The rooms were clean and bathrooms remodeled. I would definitely stay again!

The staff was exceptionally pleasant, and very welcoming! Ricky at the front desk was so appreciative of our business. The hotel itself was worth the price. It's close to AT&T Park. The inside is a little old, but clean. I saw other reviews that said the parking was difficult, but we didn't have any problems. The parking is tight, but just don't be a jerk and you'll be fine!

I've recently bought couple of things including a table runner from the clearance section. I asked the cashier about the return policy, and she said it is ok to return if the runner doesn't fit my table. The day after, I took the runner back to the store for return and another cashier told me that she can't change it because runner is a seasonal product. It was a very disappointing moment for me. I really cannot believe how they game their customers. Cashier was rude, she didn't even care. This place is a joke. I don't recommend anyone to shop here. They should learn their lesson.
The people work here all so nice especially Eric
Great furniture.
People that work in this store are n-i-c-e. Always helpful, never pushy.

Union Square.adr_address: 335 Powell St, San Francisco, CA 94102-1804, USA
Union Square.formatted_address: 335 Powell St, San Francisco, CA 94102, USA
Union Square.name: The Westin St. Francis San Francisco on Union Square

html_attributions: The Westin St. Francis San Francisco on Union Square

reviews.text:
Huge rooms right in the heart of San Fran. Most everything is within walking distance including a mall and several notable shopping locations. Nike, Tiffany's, Macy's, Cheesecake Factory, plus some local flare.

Elevators are a bit different. You have to put your key in on the outside and select your floor on the outside. That way when you get on the elevator you don't have to push any buttons. A little different, but you can get used to it.

A great place for a conference!

I love this hotel.  I've come here for business reasons to their conference room spaces,  which are excellent.  I've also stayed here for personal reasons.  Service is top notch, and the location cannot be beat... overlooking Union Square. Love it.

A nice, classy hotel that combines modernity and its rich history that is woven into San Francisco's own history. They have rotating displays of the hotels very own memorabilia and photographs of events and peoples past. Always a treat to spend time in their lobby. The rooms get great views. The glass elevator is always a joyful ride. Their public bathroom is very well-maintained and spacious.

Upgraded my family to a much larger room and with a street view. All the staff was accommodating and professional. Rooms and bathrooms will decorated and everything in good repair. My only issue was the mattress. It seemed older as it sagged in the middle and was really firm. Making for a difficult night sleep. Everything else was excellent.

Great little cafe near the registration desk. Gourmet Sandwiches and Gourmet Bakery treats. Comfortable and quiet seating area to eat them. Also, during the holidays, they always have a beautiful holiday display in the lobby. Be sure to walk out to the lobby facing Union Square to see what I mean.

Wonderful time at booty barre. I was amazed at how much of a workout it was. My prior experience with bar method was that the workout just wasn't enough, so I was very happy with booty barre.

The studio is amazingly beautiful. I've never seen one this elegant and cool. Great job who ever designed it. The location could not be better in the heart of Union Square on the cutest street in the city, Maiden Lane.
I love this yoga class

reviews.text: Bern coming here since i was a little kid, the food hv always been hot fresh and quick unless they're extremely busy, very reasonable thinking a lot of food I always take some of the servers are extremely nice it's a little loud in here with the music so it's kind of hard to have a conversation with someone. This is good for people who are drinking because it's open 24 hours..  lol

Had a late night hunger urge and took the Bart to the Castro to Orphan Andy's.  My server was awesome and very friendly.  The food definitely hit the spot and wasn't expensive.  Try it out next time you are in the area.
They are a very friendly staff and made our honeymoon a very memorable week. The food is very tasty and enjoyable. I highly recommend this for anyone coming to San Francisco.
Great diner comfort food. Staff is always very hospitable, the environment warm and welcoming. Highly recommend their Hawaiian coconut & pineapple cake.
Our server was the best we had in the city. The food tasted home cooked and was over all good. Would recommend if you're in the Castro area of San Fran.

The Stud.adr_address: 399 9th St, San Francisco, CA 94103, USA
The Stud.name: The Stud Bar

reviews.text: This bar is a San Francisco treasure. Great shows on Tuesday and Friday nights, which push the limits of drag/burlesque/performance art, and some really fun stuff on other nights. Plus karaoke on Thursdays! If you're visiting from out of town, definitely make a pitstop here especially on a Tuesday, Thurs or Fri night.
Great bar cool people! Have to go back next time I'm in San Francisco! Make sure you stop here!

Thee oldest, and still one of the funnest Gay Bars in San Francisco! Tons of different nights, bartenders aren;t assholes and pour a good drink. A part of LGBTQ history and something that should stay as part of our community and culture.

Don't let the $10 cover charge for The Stud's Friday night Drag Show turn you away- it is totally worth it. The talent is unique and you truly feel like you're around a group of inclusive locals happy to share their party with you. After 11pm things get lively. Once the talent has finished doing lip syncs everyone starts jamming to funky disco music until close. During last call the bar tenders usually won't serve anything other than shots so be ready to close the night with a bang.
No Attitude!!!!  My go to bar. and anything and everything is there. Bears, Twinks Drag Queens. My go to bar. Go see for yourself. Early 90's throwback decor. awesome

Mr. S Leather.name: Mr. S Leather

Terrible customer service, everytime I bought something here and have to get back and pick it up, never was ready and have to wait or
Come back another day, they never call you back and all their stuff is overpriced depending on the day.

There was a little mix up with the order.  Customer service worked to correct the matter in the most prompt of fashions.  The post office mixed up the second order ... which was ridiculous... and Mr. S Leather customer service was quick to have a resolution to ensure my order was to my by the date of my event.  Chris was truly kind and worked diligently to make everything right.

As for the floggers... they're effin amazeballs.   

Thank you Mr. S Leather
Amazing shop filled with amazing people, by far the best quality clothing and equipment. This is a invaluable resources to the community Wichita needs to be cherished

it IS pricey but they have the best selection, generally high quality stuff, and an extremely knowledgeable, friendly, helpful & service oriented staff.  they also deserve credit for supporting local community groups.

Got my first harness through Mr. S and they took the time to custom fit it for me and let me try on a few styles and colors. I love that they let me flit around the store trying things on without wearing anything in between. The other customers were also very welcoming and fun to shop with. Large selection of kink toys, great smells of leather and rubber, knowledgeable and very friendly staff. Would highly recommend to others!

St. Francis Fountain.adr_address: 2801 24th St, San Francisco, CA 94110-4213, USA
St. Francis Fountain.name: St. Francis Fountain

reviews.text: Old school diner with original breakfast dishes and a friendly staff. Portions are large and the price is good, so you'll leave happy. Come on a weekday to avoid the weekend rush. I ordered the Chef's Mess which is an amalgamation of potatoes, eggs, onions, mushrooms, melted cheese, and topped with sour cream and tomatoes. Meal comes with a side bread, I was recommended the banana bread and was not disappointed; served toasted and perfect with a little butter.
Great old SF landmark. Great food and friendly service. Good for wheelchair users - they were helpful and very accessible, although I don't know about the restroom.

I've only had the ice cream so far, but they're lovely people, although crazy busy and slightly stressed. The ice cream is simple yet very very tasty! They usually play great music too!
If there's a long line, you can still walk inside to order takeout.

Old-fashioned soda shop with solid diner-style food and comfortable booths. I'm a huge fan of the egg scramble. Huge portions, expect to easily have enough food to enjoy a second meal later. 

There was a long wait to be seated.
Awesome service. Best BLT I've ever had in my life.

Sutro Baths.adr_address: Point Lobos Ave, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
Sutro Baths.formatted_address: Point Lobos Ave, San Francisco, CA 94121, USA
Sutro Baths.name: Sutro Baths

reviews.text: This is a beautiful hiking area! The remains of the pools are beautiful. You're able to walk along the edges to get near the middle. Absolutely beautiful spot. Great for pictures, lunch, and hiking!

It's the remnants of a saltwater bath that was burned down. It has a nice view of the ocean and the crashing waves. The parking lot can get full pretty quick because the Cliff House Restaurant clients use the same parking lot as well as the visitors who come down for the Sutro Baths. 
There are walking trails that lead out of the area along the cliff which leads to the Legion of Honor (art museum). It's a very nice light hike. You will also get a nice view of the Golden Gate Bridge if it's not foggy.

Very interesting  historical landmark with rustic feel to it, and I mean literally, you could still see some old bolts that used to hold the wooden structure to concrete foundation. There is only one building left with no roof, which has graffiti all over its walls. Highly recommend visiting it with nose plugs or close friend due to funky smell from birds and other natural creatures living in the area. If you like oceans and beaches, then this is definitely a good sightseeing spot.

Dates, hang outs with friends - Sutro Baths is where you go for all your outdoor adventures.  There are ruins, a walk-in cave, a small beach to play frisbee and hold small gatherings and parties.

Only uphill from Ocean Beach, it's a spot perfect for taking that special someone for a romantic sunset picnic.  There's nothing like the sunset at Sutro Baths, where the reds, pinks and oranges of the sun kiss the clouds - and it really makes for some great photos.  Take your obligatory Michael Bay movie kiss photo here!

I also shot parts of my short film 007: I Only Need One here, although it has been photographed so as not to directly showcase the building and appear to be a vast and isolated beach.  Great spot for filmmakers looking for an epic scene.

Really beautiful walk in the park with views of the bay and the city. The ruins on the sutro baths have an interesting history. Worth a visit. Most of the path is sandy and rocky so make sure you are wearing shoes you aren't afraid of getting dirty.

reviews.text: The people there are very welcoming.
Home of the SF Tennis Club's Cal Cup every three years.  Great atmosphere where people come to play and it's packed! However it is windy and cloudy so SFSU courts are sunnier and have wind screens.
Nice courts although too close to each other
Super public courts. Pretty well protected from the too-often wind.

As far as a place for public tennis courts, this might have the most in all of SF.  That means it's good place for a tournament, exhibition, league match, etc.  The courts are right beside colorful characters within Golden Gate Park.  The clubhouse and bathrooms are decent (not great, but not bad).  The bench style seating between the levels of courts is kinda cool.

Willy's Barber Shop.adr_address: 3227 22nd St, San Francisco, CA 94110, USA
Willy's Barber Shop.name: Willy's Barber Shop

reviews.text: Forget all the hipster barber shops in the area. This place does great cuts and sick fades for less than all the other shops in the area. It's a small place though so get in early if you can. $20 a a sweet cut, can't go wrong.
Definitely ask for Joe! He's the best barber here.  His shaves are the best.

Terrible experience today September 28th 2016. I had to wait almost 40 minutes for a guy to cut my hair and when he was cutting he was taking breaks to go outside to speak with friends. Am very picky about who cuts my hair, an unfortunately for me he made a BAD JOB with my hair and beard plus he charged me $40.00.
It is a shame for the owner of that barber to loose customers for guys like that.

Great haircut from Daniel/Dan/(Willy?), but jeez was the conversion uncomfortable. He lambasted people like me (read: white software developers) for ruining the city. I get it, it's too expensive. But if the city blocks construction then prices have to rise with demand.

The rest of the time was swearing with plenty of sexist drivel. Honestly I think he was drunk, he asked his friend for a beer when I was only halfway done and was slurring his words the whole time.

I guess this is why the hipster barber shop was invented.
I always get a zero fade, and I'm pretty hard to please. No complaints here. Just a damn good hair cut.

Urban Flowers.adr_address: 4029 18th St, San Francisco, CA 94114, USA
Urban Flowers.name: Urban Flowers

reviews.text: I only went to this florist when I lived in the Castro, 8 years, and anytime I need to order flowers, still go here. Always reasonable prices, especially for SF!! Staff is always courteous and I always support minority owned businesses!

My bride and I eloped to SF and she trusted me to get her bouquet the morning of the wedding while she got her hair and makeup done. With nothing but a grainy cell phone pic and a bit of ribbon these folks quickly got a beautiful bouquet together. We could not have been happier with the result.
It's my go to flower shop for almost 10yrs, I highly recommend them!

I am apprehensive about having flowers sent and how the final arrangement will look. Often times it is very disappointing with the price you pay and what the end result is. I called them up, nice person answered and told her what I wanted and she nailed it! She even sent me a picture prior to it being delivered. From order to delivery was less than 2 hours and that is quick! Thank you for the awesome service and you also offer an awesome value for what you deliver. This is the place if you want flowers sent to someone special in SF.
Sent my daughter a birthday arrangement...fantastic generous selection of flowers in a fashionable square vase. Good value, dependable delivery...thanks folks.

Great little bar with a divey-but-friendly vibe. The drinks are super cheap and the staff are lovely - will definitely be back!

Divey bar near restaurants and the Alamo Theater. Great drink prices and has an authentic feel. Treat the bartenders well and they will treat you well. Otherwise, good luck. I've been told they are closing in 2017 due to a lease issue.

Cool old school dive with lots of quirky touches which add personality. Cheap drinks, especially at happy hour (till 8) in a slightly dingy (but dingy in a charming way) setting. Decent beer selection. It's usually pretty quiet & chill, which is no bad thing if you want to have a chat.
Men, If you own more than 5 light color button up that you wear regularly, don't come here. Women and men, if you like Kerry fancy cocktails go elsewhere

All of our guests highly expressed by the amazing food, awesome service as well as the romantic ambiance that night and the memorable wedding still lasts in our mind... Highly recommend!

One of three classic old school regal San Francisco hotel on top of Nob Hill. Been to many public functions here throughout the years. Recently went to the Tonga Room with some out of town guests and had a great time in a Tiki Polynesian homage to by gone era with large, shareable strong rum punch bowl with 4 straws. The live dance band played on top of a movable barge with rain and lightning playing in the background.

This Hotel was honestly so nice!  There was even an outdoor garden on the rooftop,  it was super fancy and amazing.  Although I didn't get to see the rooms,  if I had the option in the future,  would definitely do so!  Such a nice hotel,  except the parking situation which was a little bit annoying because I had to park in the grace cathedral parking
The Fairmont SF was a great place for our team building event. The large windows and beautiful gardens helped to create a wonderful and elegant atmosphere. The staff were attentive and polite.

Superb sight viewing location.  Room is very clean. Staff are well behaved. Really  enjoyed the property.

I will suggest all my friends to stay Fairmont San Francisco when they visit.

Muddy Waters Coffee House.formatted_address: 521 Valencia St, San Francisco, CA 94110, USA
Muddy Waters Coffee House.name: Muddy Waters Coffee House

reviews.text: Muddy Waters is a classic of the mission district: wood floors and a cosy feel, but sort of run down since it's been there for years.  The people watching here is hilarious, usually you will see some very strange interactions between mission characters.  Overall the coffee is not the best, but they have snacks, are open late and a restroom for customers that is decently clean for the mission.

This isn't some shiny, white-walled coffee shop. Muddy Waters is a staple of the mission, and been around as long as I've lived here. If you're kind to the staff (and you should be), they'll be kind back. Plenty of seating, free wifi, and a menu of food along with coffee and tea selections. It's cash only, but there's an ATM inside. If you're going to sit inside on a laptop, make sure you tip accordingly ;)

I came here because my cell phone was dying and I need some juice to catch my next Uber. Despite the name Muddy Waters the coffee house played smooth jazz. The jazz was nice while I sipped on my ice cold Sanpellegrino and recapped the day with my beautiful wife.

Decent, genuine place with a local vibe. My go-to spot. Coffee is not the greatest, but at least you are not going to look like a douche like in other places around where the regular conversation topic usually involve "how rich I am".
A coffee shop with blues in the background, plenty of space for small meetings between small groups. Food, computer friendly atmosphere, and artsy.

Dolores Park.formatted_address: 501 Dolores St, San Francisco, CA 94110, USA
Dolores Park.name: Dolores Park Cafe

I was tired and decided to lay my head while my partner finishes what she is doing.  I wake up to the manager Carlos,  engaged in a convo, yelling to call the cops because I was sleeping.  My girlfriend is African American, and here is Carlos which never once came by as a human to talk us ...but was fast to act like a racist with threats of cops. Why were we never approach in a humane manner?  What did we do for you to think it's ok to treat people line criminals?  Carlos you are racist! !worst experience I've had in a restaurant ever racist racist racist! !!
Meh. It plays its part. Expensive mediocre food. Close to park, which is good but means long lines. Never walked out mad, but I've never left feeling I made a really good call.

Line is slow moving.  Seating area is noisy and too public. Juice was like 10 oz., too small for the price.  I got up to refill my hot water and another patron was taking my chair after only a minute.  Really congested.
Their veggie breakfast burritos are top notch. I also like their Chai Latte.
The location is great and the service is good. Usually a line on weekends, it seems. If you're at Dolores park and want to use a clean bathroom, you can stop by here and buy something cheap :P

Punjab.adr_address: 2838 24th St, San Francisco, CA 94110-4214, USA
Punjab.name: Punjab Restaurant

reviews.text: Great place to grab dinner. No frills, good food. Great pho! Great neighborhood vibe. Nice big plates at a good price! I'm a regular!
This is now my favorite Chinese food spot at the moment. I definitely enjoy eating here. The portions are enormous for the price
The food was pretty cheap with good portions and came out lightning fast. I ordered the garlic chicken, and while it was not the most flavorful, it did the job.
Delicious and fast food for a reasonable price, would definitely go again if I lived in the area. I had the Mongolian beef and it was very spicy, which was amazing.
The food tasting terrible,bad food quality,the don't have dishwasher machine.

Financial District.adr_address: 750 Kearny St, San Francisco, CA 94108, USA
Financial District.formatted_address: 750 Kearny St, San Francisco, CA 94108, USA
Financial District.name: Hilton San Francisco Financial District

reviews.text: Huge fan of this hotel. They go above and beyond for their guests. Location is key in SF and good thing I chose this hotel. Your about 2-3 miles from all the main attractions. About 30 different restaurants within a 5 minute walk. They have a lounge to watch TV, high tech wine bar, restaurant and large ballroom in the hotel. The main 5 level garage is located underground. Our king size bed room had a large desk with plenty of counter space, large drawer, and a small closet. If you are a Hilton Honors member remember to let them know you get room upgrades and free breakfast at different levels. My only complaint is the complimentary wifi is really bad and with At&t I found myself standing by the window to get signal.

Hilton SF is a wonderful venue! I am here for a 3-day research conference and the amenities are great. The place is very well-decorated and updated. Would definitely come back for a stay in the future.

Very good Hilton hotel. I was upgraded by the receptionist despite I looked like an hillbilly. the service is great, food at the restaurant good. the lounge place is very cool, huge TV screen for sports, chairs for electronic massage. ...the room are big, nice view calm no circulation and noise from the streets.  beds are comfortable...and really you're well located IMO (in chinatown) which is a good starting point for visit.

We loved this contemporary San Francisco Hotel as our wedding venue. All of our guests, including bride and groom, all enjoyed the romantic ambiance and wonderful wedding here. Plus, the service and food here are amazing, too! I would highly recommend it to our guests!!!

Great location and friendly, helpful staff! I'm giving 4 stars instead of 5 for a few minor quibbles: checked in online and picked my room for 3pm arrival, arrived to find my selection wouldn't be ready until 6pm, very weak in room wifi and long elevator waits. Honestly, though, these are minor issues and I enjoyed my stay and would stay there again.

Wine Impression.adr_address: 3461 California St, San Francisco, CA 94118-1836, USA
Wine Impression.formatted_address: 3461 California St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
Wine Impression.name: Wine Impression

reviews.text: Solid selection of California, Italian and French wines, and pretty much whatever liqueurs you want for making cocktails. Also have a cold case with beer, Belgian ales, and white wine. Easy to park in the back of Laurel Village.
The best wine store in the city. So helpful and friendly. Incredible wines at all price points.

Claire Lilienthal Elementary School.adr_address: 3950 Sacramento St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA
Claire Lilienthal Elementary School.formatted_address: 3950 Sacramento St, San Francisco, CA 94118, USA

Yerba Buena Gardens.adr_address: 760 Howard St, San Francisco, CA 94103-3119, USA
Yerba Buena Gardens.formatted_address: 760 Howard St, San Francisco, CA 94103, USA
Yerba Buena Gardens.name: Yerba Buena Gardens Festival

reviews.text: The festival is one of my all-time, favorite things to do in SF! Live music from super incredible artists, poetry, traditional and contemporary dance, and tons more...all free and open to the public. Absolutely the BEST. Plus the gardens are a beautiful place to enjoy live music. Just put out a blanket, relax, and enjoy. Rinse and repeat, all summer long.

I love the Yerba Buena Gardens Festival! It is a beautiful space, and the musicians and artists chosen to perform are amazingly talented, and it's always fun to go see a show there. And it's free!!! In fact, I had knee surgery several years ago, and a week into my recovery I still managed to get myself to the Gardens to catch the show, crutches and all. I wasn't supposed to be on my feet, but I knew it was worth the risk :)

Amazing performances by world renown artists, relaxing atmosphere, multicultural and family friendly programming at one of the most beautiful parks. Overall, the festival embodies the spirit of San Francisco.
Live bands during the summer!

I've never been to an event here but it's nice to stop and just sit in a park that's not covered in homeless people to relax. There are so many places in this area to just grab and lunch and hang out in with friends are or on your own.

Tonga Room.adr_address: 950 Mason St, San Francisco, CA 94108, USA
Tonga Room.formatted_address: 950 Mason St, San Francisco, CA 94108, USA
Tonga Room.name: Tonga Room & Hurricane Bar

reviews.text: Very trendy. Definitely a special occasion place. Good food and drinks. There is live music and it's real good. The ambience here is something else. Try it out, you won't be disappointed.

Drinks: I found all the drinks very sweet; both their special drinks and standard cocktails.

Ambiance/Space: loved it! There's a pool inside with rain that comes on from time to time. When I went, there was a live band playing on a boat in the pool which was loads of fun. They have a dance floor where people from all ages are dancing! They've got high tables for standing as well as normal tables to sit.

Entrance: there are two entrances; one from the main lobby of the hotel and the other is from the backside of the hotel.

Cheesy and fun, is the best way to describe this place. The cocktails are expensive (but then all cocktails in SF are expensive) but tasty and well made. There is table service, here you will get a great view of the rain storm and the band which is on a boat! Great night out!

Interesting interior. Good cosy lighting. The food choices are pretty good. I tried the Kahlua pork served with red cabbage coleslaw and some sort of brioche bread, it was excellent (maybe a bit too small portion for me). The scorpion bowl was not bad, but nothing special to be honest. There was an entertainment fee of $7 per person, which I didn't know about before we came to the restaurant. Having reserved a table since long ago and since we're only in SF for a few days it felt like we had no choice but to accept that. I'm not saying that $7 is a lot, but I don't like the idea of having to pay extra for my dinner just because someone is playing in the room while I eat. I would probably feel different if I knew this beforehand and knew the band who would be playing.
Food was good, Service was phonaminal at every level. It rivaled any place Ive been anywhere in the U.S. including high end restaurants. Really was something special to find anymore.

reviews.text: Lots of great stuff to do. Need to check it out.

The SS Jeremiah O'Brien is a cargo ship, docked at Pier 45 and is the last Liberty ship in existence that supplied the Allied invasion of Normandy- also known as D-Day in the year 1944. She is operated by a volunteer crew and is still fully operational and  cruises the bay.
You can tour the ship every day from 9am - 4pm, almost all areas of the ship are open. See the Triple Expansion Steam engine that was featured in the movie, Titanic. Regular admission $12, Seniors $8, special pricing for kids, students and families. Non-profit, Historic Landmark, Historic Steam Landmark.

If you're ever curious what it takes to unload boats off a SF pier or want to buy some super fresh fish, you ought to take a peek.  It's definitely not a glamour place, nor will a visit guarantee that you'd get to see a boat unloading, but it definitely makes you appreciate the work it takes to get fresh fish to your plate and into your belly!

I was looking for a good dentist in the city and asked my coworkers at Google if they knew of any good Dentists in San Francisco. Someone recommended Washington Square Park Dental. I went and just have to say Dr. Choi did a fantastic job. She was very patient, explained to me in detail the issues with my teeth and what they were going to do to fix it. Getting the job done right was so important to me as I was leaving for Africa and Europe for 4 months. They seemed to have all the latest dental equipment and the staff was very professional and polite. I was so happy with the service I felt that the right thing to do is to help get the word about this really great dentist. If you're looking for a high quality dentist Dr. Choi is your girl! 
-Omar

I appreciated the phone call from the doctor 24 hours in advance to talk about any concerns I may have. Definitely recommend.

Jamie Zubrow DDS has taken care of me every time I've been in for an appointment. She makes me feel comfortable from the second she greets me at the chair. She also explains things really clearly so I understand what is going on inside my mouth and what options I have if/when something needs to be addressed. Thank you for being a great dentist Jamie!

reviews.text:
My experience started over 20 years ago with the SS Jeremiah.  It was one of my young son's favorite destinations.  My daughter also spent a summer volunteering in the ships store while in high school, which was invaluable on many levels.
  
I have been on a number of the cruises and events on the ship and they have always been well organized, had great food and music, and well worth the price of the tickets.  The fact that the ship is run by volunteers, and many WW11 veterans, makes each event  a very special experience.  Talking about their past wartime and peace experiences while on the ship, brings it to life, and makes one appreciate what the SS Jeremiah contributed to the war efforts.  I would highly recommend a visit to the SS Jeremiah Obrien, as well as booking a ticket  on one of the events or cruises.  It is a wonderful family adventure, for both young and old!

Great Fleet Week cruise.  A little pricey, but it's amazing that this can still power itself.  We anchored at the north east corner of the airshow performance box after cruising out the Golden Gate and back.  Food, drinks, and snacks were plentiful, but if you're not big on hot dogs for lunch, pack a sandwich.  The engine room in operation is not to be missed!

This ship is still operational and in decent condition. The self guided tour is simple but a neat way to explore this historic ship. My only complaint is that the whole experience of stepping back into the past is frequently interrupted by modern day items in the bunk rooms and even trash/recycling bags scattered about.

I volunteered for crew on the JO'B.  I helped found the overnight program for youth.  There is a great operating and docent crew on board most days. It's worth your parking hassle and boarding fee to visit to see great museum, exhibits and operating steam engine (on steaming weekends.)
Attend a food/wine/beer event or take a cruise on holidays or Fleet Week.
